{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656340"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:11:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:11:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18721"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18721"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.09,0,0.73,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77065"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11453"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18721"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62571"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10573"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26516"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26523"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77065"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe process of penile erection involves complex vascular changes mediated by the autonomic nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the vascular changes that occur during penile erection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arteriolar vasoconstriction with increased venous outflow","Arteriolar vasodilation with increased venous outflow","Equal changes in arterial inflow and venous outflow","Arteriolar vasodilation with decreased venous outflow","Arteriolar vasoconstriction with decreased venous outflow"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArteriolar vasodilation with decreased venous outflow\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the vascular changes during penile erection. Parasympathetic stimulation causes release of nitric oxide, leading to smooth muscle relaxation in arterioles and erectile tissue. The increased arterial flow fills the corpus cavernosum, while expansion of erectile tissue compresses venous outflow channels against the rigid tunica albuginea, trapping blood within the penis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArteriolar vasodilation with increased venous outflow\u003C/strong\u003E - While vasodilation occurs, venous outflow must decrease to maintain erection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArteriolar vasoconstriction with decreased venous outflow\u003C/strong\u003E - Vasoconstriction would prevent increased blood flow needed for erection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArteriolar vasoconstriction with increased venous outflow\u003C/strong\u003E - This combination would prevent blood accumulation in erectile tissue\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqual changes in arterial inflow and venous outflow\u003C/strong\u003E - Unequal changes are necessary to trap blood in erectile tissue\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of increased arterial inflow and decreased venous outflow allows blood to accumulate in the corpus cavernosum, producing and maintaining erection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Penile erection requires parasympathetic-mediated vasodilation of arterioles and relaxation of smooth muscle in erectile tissue.","Nitric oxide is the primary vasodilator responsible for penile erection through increasing cyclic guanosine monophosphate.","Blood becomes trapped in the corpus cavernosum due to compression of venous outflow channels against the tunica albuginea."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62571"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18721"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62571"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T23:38:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T23:38:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11453"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77065"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4934","li